Command-Line Proficiency:
Utilized the Linux command-line interface to interact with the operating system, navigate directory structures, and execute security-related tasks.

File Permission Management:
Applied commands to view and modify user, group, and world permissions for critical system files to ensure data privacy.

Access Control Enforcement:
Managed file ownership and access levels to uphold the principle of confidentiality, preventing unauthorized users from viewing or modifying sensitive assets.

Security Auditing via CLI:
Used Linux tools to identify improperly configured permissions that could lead to unauthorized access or potential malware deployment.

System Resource Monitoring:
Executed instructions telling the computer to monitor system activity for signs of malicious activity or unauthorized intrusions.


Example of commands used: chmod (to change permissions), chown (to change ownership), or ls -l (to view permissions) as well as Automations to remove human error.
